Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:47 PM Defendant Bryan David Reneau appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Michael Charles Hoffman appeared by video for Bryan David Reneau.  Prosecuting attorney Chad C La Lor in court for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant's address confirmed. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, and requests a preliminary hearing. State asks $10,000 cash. No contact with minors. May have contact with own child if parameters are set with DHHS. State notes that cash is based on nature of charges. Notes that there are only 2 counts but in excess of 300 photos on his device. State is still waiting for report of previous criminal history. Attorney Hoffman notes that defendant has resided in county for over 20 years and has two local jobs, would likely lose employment if he is not able to be released. Defendant does not have prior convictions. Defendant has no money to post. Asks for up to $5000 cash. Court notes concerns over nature of charges and potential penalties. 
Court orders $10,000 cash bail. No contact with minors with exception of may have contact with own child pursuant to parameters set by Douglas County DHHS. No use of internet by cell phone or storage of images on cell phone.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for September 14, 2022 at 08:30 am.
